title: NHWC Resize optimization
body:
The optimization consists of:

* Use int32_t instead of int64_t
* Use different code path for tf_crop_and_resize or other
  coordinate_transformation_mode to avoid redundant conditions
* Loop-invariant code motion of offset, coefficient and extrapolation_value
  check
* Use fixed point to avoid floating-point computation

Besides, it always transforms NCHW Resize to NHWC because it has higher perf in
the NHWC variant when the input X is 4D int8/uint8 tensor and the mode is
linear on ARM.

It improves DeepLab V3 with int8 quantization by 26%~27% on big core and 37% on
LITTLE core on AArch64. It also improves DeepLab V3 with uint8 quantization by
24%~25% on big core and 34% on LITTLE core on AArch64.

Co-authored-by: Yufeng Li <liyufeng1987@gmail.com>

title: [Bug] Mixing negative and positive paddings causes segfault/uninitialized memory values produced in reflected pad

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
**Describe the bug**
Say `a=[0, 1, 2, ..., N-1]` is passed to a 1-D Pad op with `mode='reflect'` and `padding=[-(N-1), N-1]`. ORT produces seg-fault or values that look like garbage memory (depending on N). 

I am guessing that ORT performs the negative padding (i.e., slicing) before the reflected padding. So it will remove the first `N-1` elements from `a`, at which point there are not enough elements to be "reflected". 

I tried reading the code related to Pad. Though not able to fully understand it, the logic appears to verify my guess:  https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/0869f4f4ea9abeb4edf2e5d5b570880f77f81bfa/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/pad.cc#L327 this line slices the input. Afterwards, in
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/0869f4f4ea9abeb4edf2e5d5b570880f77f81bfa/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/pad.cc#L421-L427
L421 copies the after-slicing data into a new and smaller buffer `output` and perform the reflected padding at L426-427. This smaller buffer has no enough elements to "reflect" in this case, and out-of-bound array accessing follows, causing the errors.

**Urgency**
None

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04):Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 0869f4f4ea9abeb4edf2e5d5b570880f77f81bfa
- Python version: 3.7.11
- Visual Studio version (if applicable):
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): clang version 11.1.0-++20211011094159+1fdec59bffc1-1~exp1~20211011214614.8
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 11.2
- GPU model and memory: RTX2080, 8GB

**To Reproduce**
Run this script:

```python
import onnxruntime as ort
import onnx
from onnx import helper
from onnx import AttributeProto, TensorProto, GraphProto
import numpy as np
import sys
N = int(sys.argv[1])
print('testing N=', N)
x = helper.make_tensor_value_info('x', TensorProto.FLOAT, [N])
y = helper.make_tensor_value_info('y', TensorProto.FLOAT, [N])
pads = np.array([-(N - 1), (N - 1)], dtype=np.int64)

node = helper.make_node(
    'Pad',
    inputs=['x', 'pads'],
    outputs=['y'],
    mode='reflect'
)

graph_def = helper.make_graph(
    [node],        # nodes
    'test-model',      # name
    [x],  # inputs
    [y],               # outputs
    initializer=[helper.make_tensor('pads', TensorProto.INT64, [2], pads)]
)

model_def = helper.make_model(graph_def, producer_name='onnx-example')
onnx.checker.check_model(model_def, full_check=True)
onnx.save(model_def, "output.onnx")

x = np.arange(N, dtype=np.float32)
print('input=')
print(x)
# print(f'input=[0,1,...,{N-1}]')
print(f'padding=[-{N-1}, {N-1}]')
print('output=')
y_ort = ort.InferenceSession("output.onnx", provider_options=[
    "CPUExecutionProvider"]).run(["y"], {"x": x})[0]
print(y_ort)
```

**Expected behavior**
It appears that ORT supports Pad op using both negative and positive paddings at the same time (and ONNX [spec](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/main/docs/Operators.md#pad) also doesn't seem to prohibit this). 
- If that is the case, this sounds like a bug. Hope it can be an easy fix, e.g., passing the original buffer to the 2nd argument of `PadInnermostAxis` seems to do the job, but I unfortunately don't know the code well enough to make the patch
- If not, would be great to have a check that rejects mixed positive and negative padding, instead of segfault or silently producing incorrect values. 

**Screenshots**
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7333325/173266377-7066094f-89af-4a89-b14d-70762db4c559.png)

and the stack trace for segfault run:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7333325/173272717-b51c3302-0edd-4889-9aee-786dac323c1c.png)

title: RFC: register fallback CPU kernel
body:
New contributor here - appreciate any feedback, context I might be missing, or questions! 

**Description**: register fallback CPU kernel for eager mode operations

**Motivation and Context**
Currently, if a PyTorch operation is run against ORT backend that results in an aten operation without an explicitly registered implementation, the operation will fail. ONNX has explicitly registered "TorchFallback" implementations for several operations which are not supported in onnxruntime, but if an operation is encountered that is not explicitly registered, the operation will fail.

This change is to:

1. Register a fallback CPU kernel so any unregistered operations will automatically fallback to the fallback CPU kernel.
2. Remove unused `MakeTorchFallback` logic

The intention is to enable all operations targeting ORT backend to succeed (albeit with performance hit) without explicitly registering CPU fallback for individual operations.

**Background**

This change leverages the boxed CPU fallback kernel introduced in pytorch/pytorch#58065. This allows backends to register a single boxed fallback CPU kernel that gets called if there is no other registration for the operation.

**Future Work**
A future change could be to log the calls to fallback CPU kernel in order to identify operations that are not handled by onnxrutime. This would have advantages over having the model crash, in that we could get a list of all unsupported operations in a single run, rather than iterating through 1) running model and crashing on unsupported operation, 2) registering operation, 3) re-running model to find next missing unsupported operation.

**Questions**:

 - Is adding a fallback CPU kernel the right direction? Is there a reason we would want to explicitly register all operations that we want to fallback to Torch?
 -  This PR removes now unused logic (contained in isolated commits). If we don't want to remove the now unused logic, these commits can be backed out
 - Any thoughts on future work to log calls to fallback CPU kernel? Assuming that is something that is of interest, we could include that work in this PR or add in separate PR.

The GraphProto that TRT consumes must be a self-contained GraphProto which means the subgraph should not contain any outer scope values. If the subgraph has outer scope values, we need to include those values when converting GraphView to GraphProto.

The PR modifies GraphViewerToProto() to add outer scope value that is a constant initializer to the GraphProto, which makes TRT able to read the GraphProto properly.

After the https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/10632 is merged, we found that TRT EP had a regression on tiny yolov3 model. The reason is that the subgraph of the control flow "Loop" operator is missing the outer scope value.

body:
**Description**: 
After partitioning, ORT may modify the input/output nodeArg definition for fusedNode (partition) returned by DML EP at the time of partitioning. Solution:
At the time of partitioning, DML EP is capturing the original names of the input/output nodeArgNames for the fusedNode and it will use these original names while creating the DML Graph.

title: Quantize specific ops per-tensor while per_channel=True

labels.name: quantization
labels.description: issues related to quantization

body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
When `per_channel=True`, all operators that can be quantized per-channel will actually be quantized per-channel. It is not possible to specify exceptions that should be quantized per-tensor.
For instance, in a CNN with a linear layer at the end, I would like to be able to quantize all convolutional layers per-channel and the MatMul at the end per-tensor (in the case of classification, my MatMul will output a `batch_size x num_classes` tensor and  I do not want to quantize it per-channel). 

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): 1.11.1

**Describe the solution you'd like**
In the extra options, it is possible to specify for specific ops the axis to use for performing per-channel quantization (see [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/bd65acd08d06f430c73cbc1372f2aea13141130f/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/qdq_quantizer.py#L103)): `extra_options["QDQOpTypePerChannelSupportToAxis"]` which is a dictionary of type `Dict[str, int]`. I propose to use a special value (-1 or `None` for example) when the tensor should not be quantized per-channel, such as: `{"MatMul": -1}`. In that case, the method `quantize_tensor_per_channel` should call `quantize_tensor`, as it is already done [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/bd65acd08d06f430c73cbc1372f2aea13141130f/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/qdq_quantizer.py#L128) if it is not a weight.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
I did not see any other place in the codebase where this can be done conveniently.

**Additional context**
I am happy to open a PR about this but I prefer discussing it first.
The reason for this request is that some hardware manufacturers prefer dealing with quantized linear layers on a per-tensor basis.

title: Add Ort::Session constructor overload to load from std::istream
body:
**Description**: This adds a constructor overload to `Ort::Session` for loading a model from a `std::istream` object. A corresponding function `CreateSessionFromStream` is also added to the C API using a language-agnostic abstraction `OrtInputStream` which is basically a wrapper around a function callback for reading from a stream.

I also added a basic unit test for loading a model from an `std::ifstream`.

**Motivation and Context**
- Currently, it is only possible to load models from disk via a file path or from a memory buffer. In the latter case, the full model needs to be loaded in memory. This a limitation when models need to be pre-processed/transformed, loaded from the network or similar. For example, model files may be stored in compressed form on disk. Currently, the file needs to be decompressed fully to memory before it can be loaded with onnxruntime.
- `InferenceSession` already has a constructor that accepts a `std::istream` object but it appears nowhere to be used at the moment. Also, that class is not part of the public headers as far as I know, thus not intended to be used by library consumers.

This PR is currently just a draft. I would like to get some initial feedback on whether such functionality would be welcomed and if this is the way to implement it or if there is a better way.
